Southron Commander x2<br />
Desert Lord x2<br />
Army of Haradrim x2 <br />
Mumak x3<br />
War Mumak x2<br />
Howl of Harad x2 <br />
On the March x4 <br />
Whirling Strike x3<br />
Flanking Attack x2     </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> For this deck you should bid to go first at 3 or 4 burdens.  Exert Legolas and Haldir to play Gimli.  Use Skilled Defender, Gimli&#39;s Battle Axe, and Bow of the Galadrim to wound minions assigned to other companions.  Haldir is only included as another companion who can be a strength 7 and doesn&#39;t have to rely on wounds.  Play as many bows on the swordsmen and Haldir as possible to get out a lot of archery.  Then use the Lorien Swordsmen to bring down the strength of wounded minions.  The pumpers are included to make sure Legolas and Gimli keep winning their skirmishes.  Archer of Mirkwood is used to heal another companion when he wins a skirmish.  Tharin can be used when desperate and he can be used multiple times even if he loses his skirmish because of the elven allies in combination with Shoulder to Shoulder.  3 hand axes are included because Grimir and Thrarin can also use them.  Grimir is there to recycle mainly Quick as May Be but he can also bring back Khazad-Ai-Menu if it is more needed.  This is an open format elf deck so Lady of Light and the other Site 6 Elven allies are included.  Galadriel can be very useful for playing free swordsmen and also for use on Shoulder to Shoulder.  With all the elf allies out and S2S down Gimli can always be healed each turn and then Gimli can be used to heal the other elf companions in turn.<br />
The Southrons are mainly used here to stop the opposing FP.  The direct wounding can also be used to kill beefed up companions even without winning a skirmish.  Use the Southron Assassins when you can play one or two other southrons so you can use his text more than once.  Assassins are great with mumaks.  Except for RBR decks, Frodo is usually the only ring-bound companion so he can easily find himself in a bad position with the Assassinss and the Howl of Harad.  The Southron Commanders are mainly there for twilight production and a possible skirmish opportunity with the ring-bearer where whirling strike can be used.  The runners are there to produce extra twilight and try to stack on a companion (although this doesn&#39;t happen very often).  Try to get the Army of Haradrim late in the game so that you can bring back out your mumaks.  Nan Curunir is my site 8 so I can prevent wounds to mumaked Southrons.  All in all this Shadow side is good for stopping and slowing the opposing FP with an occassional kill or two. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=28528"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=28528" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
